TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Identification of Solution Ideas During Organizational Decision Making
AU  - Nutt, Paul C.
Y1  - 1993/09/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.39.9.1071
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.39.9.1071
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1071
EP  - 1085
VL  - 39
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This research investigated the idea development stage of a strategic decision making process. The tactics that decision makers apply to identify ideas were uncovered from a systematic study of 168 decision cases. These tactics and contextual factors describing the decision situation were analyzed to determine how each influences success measured by decision merit, development time, initial adoption, and sustained adoption. A ?synthesized template? which integrated useful practices and procedures from several sources had the most success, but this tactic was seldom used. A ?cyclical search? in which repeated searches were carried out to learn about opportunities was quite successful when used under conditions of low importance, low urgency, and good staff support. The success of the design tactic, which calls for innovation, improved when urgency was present and multiple alternatives were sought. The idea tactic which imposed a fully developed solution was widely used and seldom successful.
AB  - This research investigated the idea development stage of a strategic decision making process. The tactics that decision makers apply to identify ideas were uncovered from a systematic study of 168 decision cases. These tactics and contextual factors describing the decision situation were analyzed to determine how each influences success measured by decision merit, development time, initial adoption, and sustained adoption. A ?synthesized template? which integrated useful practices and procedures from several sources had the most success, but this tactic was seldom used. A ?cyclical search? in which repeated searches were carried out to learn about opportunities was quite successful when used under conditions of low importance, low urgency, and good staff support. The success of the design tactic, which calls for innovation, improved when urgency was present and multiple alternatives were sought. The idea tactic which imposed a fully developed solution was widely used and seldom successful.
